 soul, of matter and Heaven, and even probes what it is to understand understanding, reason, and substance. Far from being anti-Newtonian, Blake was prophetically post-Newtonian. His poetry and art realized the revolutionary potential of Enlightened natural philosophy even as that philosophy still needed an Einstein for its physics to snap fully into focus. Blake's mythmaking exploits the imaginative reach of formal abstractions to generate a model of how sensation imparts physical extension to the world. More striking still, Cooper shows how Blake's art of vision leads us today to visualize four-dimensional concepts of space, time, and Man for ourselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGeometry in literature. 0aLiterature and sciencezGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aMathematics in literature. 0aPhysics in literature. 0aSpace and time in literature. 4aHistory : History of Science. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Romanticism. 4aPhilosophy : Metaphysics. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849323740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438493237423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438493237/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles